Why Us? We are here to help you build with peace of mind by providing the financial resources necessary to fairly compete for construction Our core values mean that we keep our word, you have online access to all project records and there are never any hidden fees, and we treat everyone with respect and Technology Southwest Capital Group built the Professional Contractor Services Management Application so you can see the status of your projects at all times! Start Video Demo Please tell us more about you1 Click here to start! From Southwest Capital Group July , The results of the SWCG Commercial Construction Survey are in! The first question, on the main issues facing the industry, the results were The rising cost of materials was the main issue for most responders, with % overall and % of GCs selecting this Note % of the responders were GCs and % (with % of responders not specifying their company type). The ability to hire skilled labor was the second most common response, with Subs being much more likely to have an issue with finding skilled The third most common response was a delay in project start dates . Please see all the responses to this question to the Left: The second survey question was what was the biggest issue facing the commercial construction industry . The consensus was clear, the rising cost of materials and scarcity of skilled labor were the two top issues! Over % of the responders cited these two issues as the most Only two other issues, project delays and poor profit margins even received responses from the entire list of options (see prior post for the full list). While it was consistent for GC and Subs, as one might expect, Subs when often providing all the job materials, are even more concerned about the rising cost of Over % of Subs responded the cost issue as the most The higher response from Subs is even more evident when looking at how projects get completed by % of General Contractors responded that they primarily work while only 6% self Compare that to Subs, where % responded that self perform most % of responders indicate that they split self perform and use Subs In the third and fourth questions of the Commercial Contractor Survey, we asked two key First, has the rising cost of materials affected start We had heard anecdotal indications that this was true, and we wanted to collect data to It is clearly an issue as 7 in contractors responded that project have been delayed due to rising costs of The second question was related to hiring small and disadvantaged sub 2 in 3 contractors said they would like to hire more small DBE The inference is they have not been able to up to This raises the question as to why more small and minority contractors have not been hired in the What needs to happen to make hiring more small DBE firms a reality? We will explore these issues more in the next Commercial Construction Survey planned for Q4 ! May , There are tremendous challenges today for General Contractors, and Subcontractors alike, during these uncertain For those contractors able to continue to work, getting paid, a challenge in the best of times, is taking longer than Skilled labor has been in short supply for some time, but now, maintaining even back office staff is presenting new challenges since so many workers are forced to stay home by government ordinance, or to care for children home from school! We can help! QCSA - UCLA Toggle navigation Quantum Computing Student Association Home Team Events Join Us Contact Our Focus The Quantum Computing Student Association (QCSA) at UCLA is a combined undergraduate and graduate student group under the CQSE focused on everything under the umbrella of quantum information science, including quantum computers, sensors, and We welcome students of all levels who are interested in quantum computing, and try to make our events as accessible as possible! Calendar Events Speaker Events times each quarter We hold speaker events each quarter by professors and industry professionals working in the field of quantum information Past speakers include UCLA professors in the Physics, Chemistry, and CS departments, as well as industry professionals from Google, IBM, and Atom Journal Clubs times each quarter We hold journal club talks regularly, in which an undergraduate or graduate student either reads and presents on a paper they have read or talk about their own research relevant to quantum information Workshops Occasional, Starting Winter We are developing a series of introductory workshops to teach students about the basics of quantum computing, quantum programming, and quantum Qiskit Fall Fest Hackathon Fall Quarter & For the last two years, UCLA has held a hackathon during fall quarter as part of the Qiskit Fall Fest, a collection of events, workshops, and hackathons held around the This year, we had over students enter, including undergraduate, masters, and PhD As part of the hackathon, we also had a guest speaker from We re hoping to hold these every year to give students the opportunity to work together to learn about quantum EYU Fall Quarter This fall, we partnered with the Alexandrova group in UCLA s chemistry department to run and staff a booth at the annual Exploring Your Universe (EYU) event, teaching elementary school aged children the basics of probability and its connection to quantum Future Events In the future, we intend to start running workshops and more accessible, events as well as try to expand our outreach Our Team Website Ashley Shin Leadership Team Member Department: Chemistry and Biochemistry, UCLA Ashley is currently working on her PhD, studying quantum confined and quantum computing materials at UCLA with Justin She is an alumni of Washington University in Louis, where she received her BA in chemistry and computer science in In addition to her scientific endeavors, Ashley is passionate about pedagogical teaching, outreach, and She is excited to be a part of CQSE and QCSA, and wants to meet more people who share as much excitement about the development and potential of quantum information Please reach out via email, if you d like to meet her! Amanda Younes Leadership Team Member Department: Physics and Astronomy, UCLA Amanda is an undergraduate physics student interested in atomic, molecular, and optical physics and trapped ion quantum She is excited to learn more about different quantum computing hardwares and gain a more complete understanding of the opportunities in quantum information science, as well as to meet other students interested in quantum computing! Chuixin (Lambert) Kong Leadership Team Member Department: Physics and Astronomy, UCLA Lambert is an undergraduate student majoring in physics, currently working with Professor Wes Campbell on trapped ion quantum He is currently working on a frequency tripling system that stabilizes the laser conducting state detection and doppler cooling for + He is interested in learning various quantum computing hardware and quantum As part of the QCSA, he is excited to help the development of the student community of quantum computing at Will Wang Leadership Team Member Department: Physics and Astronomy, UCLA Will is a third year undergraduate student in He currently works as a undergraduate research assistant advised by Professor Hongwen Jiang at the Quantum Physics and Technology Research Laboratory at Will is interested in condensed matter physics and quantum His current research focuses on the quantum control and automated characterization of quantum dot Feel free to shoot him an email if you have any questions regarding QCSA! Utilizamos una técnica de destilación lenta para retener la mayoría de los aromas y sabores provenientes de la Separamos “cabezas” y “colas” del líquido, que en esta etapa se conoce como "ordinario". Designed on a cohort model, this small group will meet via Zoom monthly over the course of 8 months to learn practical management and leadership Although virtual, the highly interactive format provides a unique opportunity to learn from experienced facilitators as well as your We will be holding a FREE introductory session on March at :00 Contact us today to talk about the next cohort Schedule FREE (March ) A introductory Get to know Alex, get to know each other and get to know Zoom, our platform for the See below for link to complete Session 1: Intro to Systems Thinking, Infrastructure, and Operations for Managers (April ) Whether managing a single project or a team of many people, successful management requires being able to shift between and broader organizational The discussion will help people transition from focusing predominantly on their individual workload (or team workload) to understand the context of that workload within the broader – How do all the pieces connect? – How can a systems perspective provide new info about problems and help identify potential solutions? Session 2: Improving and Developing your Leadership Style (May ) Developing an authentic leadership style that works for you (meaning it fits your personality and core tendencies) increases your effectiveness when working with and influencing others and makes you a more effective and respected Being a good leader and manager requires a of ! Session 3: Getting Proactive, Intro to Risk Management (June ) This module introduces the concept of risk management: anticipating potential problems and being prepared to deal with them in a strategic way, and prioritizing and adapting in the face of many moving It’s not about avoiding risk, it’s about mitigating risk and minimizing the Stuff will Don’t be caught Session 4: Basics in HR & Employment Law (July ) The goal of this discussion is to establish basic familiarity with critical concepts and provide a framework for the participants to go back and learn about the specific policies, structures, and limitations of the HR capabilities within their Specific topics will include: Harassment, gossip and office politics When to go to HR vs what you should handle within your team Diversity and unconscious bias “At Will” employment rules EEO rules and considerations PTO and sick leave management Session 5: Managing Your Team (August ) Please note the change in weeks Exercises and discussions will highlight ways to create ideal working environment for direct reports Session 6: Strategic Communications and Difficult Conversations (September ) This module will help participants practice both planned strategic communications and responses to uncomfortable situation through several exercises with the help of a professional Session 7: Nonprofit Finance and Budgeting Basics (October ) This module will provide an overview of the team concepts of nonprofit financial management and budgeting, and how these concepts may be relevant to Basic topics will include funding sources for nonprofit organizations an overview of grants (private, government, foundation) the difference between grants and contracts restricted vs unrestricted funds different types of Session 8: Project Management Tools (November ) This module will give participants a chance to learn and practice basic project management concepts to ensure the workload under their authority is done well and completed on All sessions will be virtual and held from :00 :00 PM, You will be sent links to the seminars after you complete your Cost To make sure you receive the customized help you Remember me Sign in Recover your A password will be to   6 Useful Tips For Buying Mattress Skip to content Menu Home Auto Business Finance Health Home Improvement Law News Pets Technology Travel Home » Shopping » 6 Useful Tips for Buying Mattress 6 Useful Tips for Buying Mattress November 2, November 2, by Libby Austin It would appear natural to prefer a mattress based on its However, in the case of a mattress, looks can be You should always strive to know the actual quality of a Doing a real trial of the mattress can tell you so much about its quality and The very act of lying down on the bed and having a real feel of the same may tell you a lot about the comfort level of the mattress for your Here are few tips to help you choose the best mattress for your needs:- 1) Number of Coils, Number of Turns: According to experts, the best quality mattresses should contain a minimum of coils for a , for a queen, and for a king size one . Further, each coil should be ‘turned’ at least five times in each specifications are not But if you ask the vendors about it, he will happily tell you Moreover, you can also know about these specifications in the online manual of the mattress at vendor’s For example, by reading the Ecosa mattress review you can be pretty sure as to whether a particular brand is best suitable choice for you or 2) Your height matters Ideally, a mattress should measure at least six inches longer than the tallest person sleeping on This would ensure that each member of the family can sleep on it Moreover, a tall mattress also provides room for sufficient width space hat can accommodate more than two family members with 3) Is Just Right for most people: If your mattress is too firm, it will not be able to support your body evenly and may cause discomfort at the most substantial points (hips and shoulders). If it is too soft, there is the risk of person sinking into the bottom and having difficulty in moving, which could cause tingling, numbness, or Using a firm mattress will protect users from such discomforting 4) Hot Sleepers require heat retention The bodies of several people have a natural tendency to become warm during sleep, which results in breathlessness and If you are one of them, you should consider a foam mattress that retains heat well and have an construction for maximum This is essential not only to have a sound sleep but also from health’s point of 5) Testing the mattress : Most reputed brands offer to their customers the chance to test the mattresses in While trying out the mattress, you should lie comfortably at least for five to ten minutes minutes on it to have a real feeling of the actual Trying this resting test with pillow will be more effective as it would provide a real feeling of the mattress you would get when using it at This would be the best test for choosing the right mattress for 6) Replacing The Box Spring, Many experts say that while replacing the mattress, you should also replace its box spring It is because over time, the constant compression of the springs start affecting the the structural integrity of the box However, this is not the gospel In a survey, majority of the people were found to be sleeping better just with the replacement of mattress that is without replacing the box So the rule of thumb is that it is not always necessary to invariably change the box spring if it s not In other words, your sound sleep depends upon using the right mattress and there is no proven link between a mattress and box spring that would warranted their simultaneous Categories Shopping Post navigation Best Flooring For A Mobile Home The beauty that makes the real difference now Share on: Related Posts Where Can You Buy Bluetooth Headphones at Excellent Prices? How Solar Works » Noble Solar Skip to content How Solar Works Cost of Solar Solar Panel Installations Colorado Solar Panel Installations Virginia Solar Panel Installations About Us Contact Us How Solar Works The science behind % renewable energy for your How homes generate, use, and store excess electricity after switching to solar power Solar panels are made up of solar cells multiple panels can be wired together to create a solar When sunlight hits a solar cell, the photons knock electrons loose from their These free electrons are converted into a DC current – the basis of electricity – which then flows into an inverter, transforming the current from DC to This AC current is utilized to power your During peak hours, solar panels will typically produce more electricity than your home actively This excess energy is stored in a battery for later use, such as overnight or on cloudy Alternatively, excess energy can be funneled back into the electrical grid, collected by your utility supplier as a “credit” for you to draw from later on (a process called net metering). The more panels you use, the more electricity you can generate and Thankfully, solar power is becoming more affordable, accessible, and resilient due to recent technological advancements – so it’s likely you can make % clean, renewable energy a reality for your How much homeowners save after switching to solar Utility costs have been rising steadily in recent years, prompting many homeowners to search for alternatives to traditional energy Since solar power relies on sunlight, a free and universal resource, the right solar panel setup can ultimately reduce your electricity spending to It’s important to note, however, that the installation of solar panels does require an investment – but if you plan to stay in your home for many years, you will likely recoup those costs via savings on your utility bills (or via the increase in your home’s overall value should you decide to sell). There are several factors, ranging from the size and orientation of your home to the pitch of your roof and local climate, that will impact the exact amount of money you could If you know how much you currently spend on electricity per year, we can help you calculate your savings potential by providing a quote for installation costs and estimated solar system We’ve found that the “average” home will save anywhere from 5 – % right away, with savings increasing year after Start Your Free Solar Quote Today Click here How to find out if solar is right for your home Not every home is set up for solar However, with the right modifications, most homes can be altered to accommodate at least a small solar array to offset carbon emissions and save money on When we perform an initial solar inspection for our clients, we ask questions about the size and orientation of your home, the amount of tree cover, and the type and pitch of your If you have too much shade due to tree cover, we may suggest either trimming or removing trees to make your investment On the other hand, if you get enough hours of sunlight on your , , or roof sections, you are likely a good candidate for How to find out if you qualify for solar incentives There are a number of incentives offered by both state and federal governments that are designed to encourage businesses and homeowners to pursue renewable energy – including At the federal level, homeowners currently qualify for a tax credit equal to percent of the cost of their solar panel system (minus any cash rebates). State tax credits are also available but vary widely from state to Cash rebate programs are frequently offered by states, municipalities, utility companies, or other organizations that want to promote solar energy You may also be able to qualify for a subsidized solar loan with a reduced interest rate to help you pay for your solar installation qualification is typically based on credit score, bankruptcy history, and the title status of your To learn more about state and federal incentives for solar, visit the Database of State Incentives for Renewables & Efficiency® website How to schedule an inspection to find out eligibility, installation cost, incentives, monthly savings, and more If you’re interested in installing solar panels at your home, contact us to schedule a free initial consultation with our team of This conversation should only take about 5 minutes: We’ll ask basic questions about your current electricity usage, goals, and any concerns you may We’ll also need to know about the type, condition, and orientation of your roof and the amount of daily shade versus sun Next, we’ll schedule an or virtual (Zoom or Skype) appointment to perform a more evaluation of your home and go over equipment, costs, logistics, and next We’ll discuss relevant state and federal incentive programs and how to qualify, providing a realistic estimate of the costs and potential Our goal is to help you learn as much as possible about solar technology so you can g
